    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA234-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">Unidentified poem quoted in <term xml:lang="ta">Iḷampuraṇār</term>’s commentary on TP 112 (ib. p. 374) as an illustration of "<term xml:lang="ta">arumaiyiṉ akaṟci</term>", thus also Nacc. on TP 114 (ib. p. 95), and Nakk. on IA 12 (p. 91).</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA234">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nerunalum muṉṉā ḷellaiyu moruciṟaip</l>
<l>            putuvai yākali ṉataṟkeyta nāṇi</l>
<l>            nēriṟai vaḷaittō ṇiṉtōḻi ceyta</l>
<l>            vāruyir varuttaṅ kaḷaiyā yōveṉa</l>
<l>            veṟkuṟai yuṟuti rāyiṉ coṟkuṟai </l>
<l>            yempatat teḷiya ḷalla ḷemakkōr</l>
<l>            kaṭkāṇ kaṭavuḷ allaḷō peruma</l>
<l>            vāykōṉ miḷakiṉ malaiyaṅ koḻuṅkoṭi</l>
<l>            tuñcupuli varippuṟan taivaru</l>
<l>            mañcucūḻ maṇivarai maṉṉavaṉ makaḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Having been ashamed to reach out for that<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ataṟku eyta</term>: here Nacc. reads almost like a gloss: <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷattal</term> - "having been ashamed to express yourself clearly".</note> since you are a newcomer,</l>
<l rend="indent3">on one side yesterday and throughout the previous days,</l>
<l rend="indent2">if you should have a request to me, saying</l>
<l rend="indent3">“won’t you remove the suffering of [my] difficult life</l>
<l rend="indent3">that has been caused by your friend with fine-jointed bangled arms?”,</l>
<l>– she is not easy of approach for us<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">em patattu eḷiyaḷ allaḷ</term>: this is a little bit problematic for syntax. We can take <term xml:lang="ta">patam</term> as "occasion" like above, and then we have to read <term xml:lang="ta">em</term> as an unmarked dative, which is not very usual. Or we can take patam as a word for place and read it as a locative suffix, and then we have to complement the elliptical predicate, she is not easy in which respect.</note> for worded requests.</l>
<l>Is she not like a<note place="foot">T.V.G. interprets <term xml:lang="ta">ōr</term> as one, and, indeed, that is tempting, but it is problematical here for form as well as for position. It is separated from <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭavuḷ</term> (a goddess seen with one eye would not be overly convincing), and there is no vowel following, so there is no reason why it should not be <term xml:lang="ta">oru</term>.</note> goddess seen with the eyes to us, o great one?</l>
<l>[She is] the daughter of the king of the sapphire mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent4">surrounded by clouds,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the rich mountain creeper of the black pepper with choice stems</l>
<l rend="indent2">rubs the striped back of a sleeping tiger.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
